[3] Saudi Arabia (Jeddah)
Date: Tue 27 Jul 2004
From: Shamsudeen Fagbo <oloungbo@yahoo.com>
Source: Arab News.com 27 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://arabnews.com/?page=1Â§ion=0&article=48960&d=27&m=7&
y=2004&pix=kingdom.jpg&category=Kingdom>

A 2nd Saudi has died in a private hospital in Jeddah as a result of
dengue fever, Okaz daily reported yesterday [Mon 26 Jul 2004].
The cases of suspected dengue fever reported in Jeddah hospitals have
now reached 251. Of these, 145 cases were confirmed by laboratory
tests. Most of these cases were treated, and only 11 patients remain
in the hospital.
A health care official in Jeddah said the health department was
monitoring the situation, which was brought under control thanks to
preventive measures adopted by the disease-control team. The official
said a number of precautionary measures have been taken to prevent
the disease from spreading. These include spraying mosquitoes, and
their breeding areas, and increasing public awareness about the
disease.
In Saudi Arabia, the water-rich areas around Najran are high-risk
areas. Other parts of the country, especially cities in the Western
Region, are also vulnerable, as visitors from infected regions, or
other countries, may arrive carrying the virus.
