[4] Singapore
Date: 27 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Channel News Asia, 27 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/978 43/1/.html>

Yishun reports highest number of dengue cases in a week
-----------------------------------------------
The number of dengue cases surged last week [3rd week July 2004],
with Yishun being the worst affected area. A total of 222 cases were
reported, compared to a weekly average of 68 earlier in 2004. The
National Environment Agency [NEA] said warmer weather, and
intermittent rain, were partly to blame for the high numbers.
The most affected area, so far, is Ang Mo Kio, where about 300 cases
were reported this year [2004]. Yishun is next, with about 230 cases.
Most of the cases happened just last week [3rd week July 2004],
making that week the peak of dengue in Singapore in 2004.
The majority of the dengue cases in Yishun were caused by indoor
mosquito breeding, including the breeding of mosquitoes along the
corridors. The most common breeding grounds are flower pot plates.
All it takes is just a few drops of water in the plate for the Aedes
mosquitoes to breed. The NEA said more households were breeding
mosquitoes, some 2 to 3 times more, than just a few years ago.
Mr. Khoo Seow Poh, Director-General of Public Health at NEA, said:
"everyone knows stagnant water breeds mosquitoes, but, they need to
have the habit to clear stagnant water once a week. It is a question
of discipline and playing their part in removing sources of mosquito
breeding." The NEA hopes to reverse this trend by raising awareness
through its "Mozzie Attack" campaign, and it has spent over SGD 8
million [USD 4 629 000] fighting dengue in 2004.
[Byline: Derek Cher]
