[5] Singapore
Date: Thu 29 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AP in Canadian Press, 28 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.canada.com/search/story.html?id=d2943e87-7896-42b7-
b3c2-057a7534867e>

Nearly 3000 dengue cases in Singapore; authorities blame standing water
-----------------------------------------------
Cases of dengue fever in Singapore could surpass a 5-year high in
2004, with authorities blaming the trend on a significant increase in
the number of mosquitoes breeding in public housing.
An average of 103 people a week in Singapore contracted dengue fever,
bringing the total, so far this year [2004], to nearly 3000 cases,
with one fatality, National Environment Agency spokeswoman Jacqueline
See said.
The latest figures follow an already 5-year high in the city-state
last year [2003], when 4772 people were infected, and 6 died, with
the mosquito-borne disease that is characterized by high fever,
headaches, aching joints, and skin rashes.
The NEA said, on its web-site, that the upsurge was due to a
"worrying trend" in the rising number of homes in which standing
water was present, allowing mosquitoes to breed. The agency estimated
that 18 of every 1000 public housing flats bred the insects, triple
the number from 2003. Around 80 percent of Singapore's 4 million
citizens live in public housing. The tightly controlled city-state
issues fines for people who leave watering cans, buckets, and other
containers with stagnant water, in the open.
